1
00:00:00,706 --> 00:00:08,474
Foundation Course 2, Talk 5, The Divine Abodes The First Noble Truth states that life itself is suffering.

2
00:00:09,076 --> 00:00:21,271
A great deal of conversation and talks from monks, nuns and lay people in Buddhism tend to concentrate on the problem of suffering, physical pain, mental anguish or social injustice and so on, and how we are to overcome it.

3
00:00:22,152 --> 00:00:29,481
But too little is said of life after you do overcome these tribulations, or what life is like when all suffering is dispelled.

4
00:00:30,035 --> 00:00:36,764
Is life without pleasure-seeking and without mental anguish just a bland existence, a sort of grey emotional life where nothing happens?

5
00:00:38,185 --> 00:00:41,951
The Buddha grew up in a society where the dominant beliefs were known as Brahmanism.

6
00:00:42,771 --> 00:00:46,517
The chief priests of this society were known as Brahmins, meaning followers of Brahma.

7
00:00:46,838 --> 00:00:52,826
In fact, the early followers of the Buddha did not call themselves Buddhists, but Sadamins, followers of the real truth.

8
00:00:53,987 --> 00:00:57,612
Brahma was the highest god and the purpose of life for Brahmanism was

9
00:00:58,030 --> 00:01:01,215
the summation of all their endeavour was to be one with Brahma.

10
00:01:02,517 --> 00:01:16,140
Since the Buddha declared there was no personality god or creator or divine being, Brahma was demoted to being the chief inhabitant of the highest heavenly plane, or Brahma was seen as the highest mind achievable by human beings before Nirvana.

11
00:01:17,200 --> 00:01:32,795
So when the Buddha was asked what was it like to be a Brahma realm dweller, a being whose mind was so highly developed, he replied that such a being was always within one of four mental states, loving-kindness, compassion, sympathetic joy, or equanimity.

12
00:01:33,474 --> 00:01:40,441
In other words, the greatest God, or the highest mind in all the universe, dwelt in those sorts of mental states all the time.

13
00:01:41,683 --> 00:01:46,987
The enlightened mind, the Buddha, the saint, or Arahant, while alive, dwells always within these states.

14
00:01:47,507 --> 00:01:50,753
So this is the end product mentally of all our training.

15
00:01:51,474 --> 00:01:56,942
All this work we are doing on ourselves in meditation sitting and mindfulness in meditative life.

16
00:01:58,424 --> 00:02:00,888
This is what we as meditators are aiming to achieve.

17
00:02:01,168 --> 00:02:06,376
A mind continually in states of friendliness, compassion, sympathetic joy or equanimity.

18
00:02:06,930 --> 00:02:20,455
Unlike nibbana, unlike transcendental insight, which is beyond our power to control, these four dwelling places of Brahma, the Brahma-vihara, or the divine abodes, as they are called, can actually be developed by us in a positive and active way.

19
00:02:21,597 --> 00:02:30,913
As these states of mind become more and more developed in us, we will scotch the myth that Buddhism is a selfish path, teaching a way of detachment and cold indifference.

20
00:02:32,664 --> 00:02:34,768
The highest of the four states is equanimity.

21
00:02:35,348 --> 00:02:40,695
Equanimity means a balanced mind, a mind that is impartial, does not get caught up in opinions and views.

22
00:02:41,417 --> 00:02:50,207
It is the mind within which the intuition has full freedom, unencumbered by prejudice, bias or any delusion, a mind that is at peace with itself and with the world.

23
00:02:51,188 --> 00:02:59,280
Equanimity is the peaceful heart, calm, untroubled, like a placid lake, in whose waters the sky is mirrored perfectly without distortion.

24
00:03:00,526 --> 00:03:05,092
We can test our own equanimity in the way we react to what the Buddha calls the eight worldly conditions.

25
00:03:05,713 --> 00:03:12,604
These are gain and loss, fame and loss of fame, praise and blame, happiness and pain.

26
00:03:14,266 --> 00:03:20,597
True equanimity does not arise out of indifference, a sort of what does it matter anyway, a carelessness, an apathy.

27
00:03:21,418 --> 00:03:24,643
This sort of attitude is actually callousness, a hardening of the heart.

28
00:03:25,096 --> 00:03:35,768
True equanimity arises out of wisdom in sight, the personal experiential knowledge that everything is passing, the personal experiential knowledge that there is no permanent self in the body and mind.

29
00:03:36,729 --> 00:03:39,953
There is nothing that constitutes a permanent ego, a substantial self.

30
00:03:40,614 --> 00:03:44,437
Nothing in reality belongs to a me, is a mine.

31
00:03:45,139 --> 00:03:51,306
Whether we win a million on the pools or lose it all on the dogs, we remain equanimous, even-minded, calm.

32
00:03:52,146 --> 00:03:54,770
Sometimes we have many friends, many parties to go to.

33
00:03:54,789 --> 00:03:58,133
Other times we seem to be alone, unwanted, devoid of friendship.

34
00:03:58,752 --> 00:04:01,075
Yet we remain even-minded, calm-hearted.

35
00:04:02,016 --> 00:04:06,621
Sometimes at work, in the family, everyone is praising us, saying how wonderful we are, what successes.

36
00:04:07,502 --> 00:04:13,807
Other times we can't seem to do anything right, the boss breathing down our necks, the husband, the wife, the kids all complaining.

37
00:04:14,368 --> 00:04:18,913
Praise or blame, we remain even, unruffled, our hearts calm and peaceful.

38
00:04:20,108 --> 00:04:23,211
Many is the time we wake up happy, life's wonderful, we're going on holiday.

39
00:04:23,612 --> 00:04:26,315
Many is the time we wake up dreadful, life's terrible, we're going to work.

40
00:04:27,177 --> 00:04:29,819
What does it matter to the even-minded, the calm-hearted?

41
00:04:30,922 --> 00:04:37,329
Whatever happens, in the person whose equanimity is highly developed, she remains balanced in mind, clear-sighted.

42
00:04:38,091 --> 00:04:40,774
He remains calm in heart, peaceful within himself.

43
00:04:42,797 --> 00:04:46,841
This mental quality of equanimity is extremely important in our meditation practice.

44
00:04:47,428 --> 00:04:50,896
Awareness is the brightness of the mind, that knowing what is happening.

45
00:04:51,656 --> 00:04:59,351
Equanimity is the ability of the mind to stay with the object of meditation without getting caught up in it, without reacting to it.

46
00:05:00,694 --> 00:05:04,442
When we are meditating we can occasionally make a mental check.

47
00:05:04,826 --> 00:05:05,869
Am I really aware?

48
00:05:06,408 --> 00:05:07,290
Am I really awake?

49
00:05:07,971 --> 00:05:09,134
Am I really equanimous?

50
00:05:09,855 --> 00:05:11,697
Am I really still, deep inside?

51
00:05:12,718 --> 00:05:20,870
Is my awareness sitting in the stillness of equanimity, or is it desperately trying to hold its own, fighting against the onslaughts of emotion and thoughts?

52
00:05:22,012 --> 00:05:29,805
If we see in our meditation that we are losing this balance, this calmness, we should go back to the breath until we re-establish the equanimous calm base.

53
00:05:31,490 --> 00:05:40,483
When we realize the role of equanimity in meditation, how important it is to establish a calm, balanced mind, we also come to know how important it is in our daily lives.

54
00:05:41,867 --> 00:05:48,357
No matter what negativity we feel in ourselves, we just observe it and keep that still center within us.

55
00:05:49,519 --> 00:05:55,788
No matter what negativity we are facing from another , we don't lose our balance.

56
00:05:56,810 --> 00:05:58,492
We are aware of our reactions.

57
00:05:58,759 --> 00:06:01,223
but we don't entertain them and act from that point.

58
00:06:01,944 --> 00:06:04,708
We don't react to outside stimuli, outside causes.

59
00:06:05,307 --> 00:06:11,175
We act from, we move outward from the center of balance, the equipoise, the calm heart and mind.

60
00:06:12,677 --> 00:06:13,738
But how do we move out?

61
00:06:13,798 --> 00:06:16,302
How do we respond from this center of inward balance?

62
00:06:17,324 --> 00:06:22,269
The way we will respond will be in the three other modes, the three other divine abodes.

63
00:06:22,704 --> 00:06:35,596
If our response to ourselves and to others is coming from that inner stillness where intuitive wisdom resides, we will always respond with loving kindness, or compassion, or sympathetic joy, as the situation warrants.

64
00:06:36,257 --> 00:06:41,283
And where these reactions are inappropriate, we will simply remain calm, balanced, equanimous.

65
00:06:41,944 --> 00:06:43,685
Equanimity is our home base.

66
00:06:46,007 --> 00:06:49,271
Before we go further, I'd like to introduce you to a very important work.

67
00:06:50,271 --> 00:06:51,733
Once the Buddha died, of course,

68
00:06:52,084 --> 00:06:55,189
there grew up an industry of commentary and commentary upon the commentaries.

69
00:06:56,069 --> 00:07:03,319
The original commentaries are also considered very much part of the Theravada teaching, and other schools of Buddhism also have their own commentaries.

70
00:07:04,341 --> 00:07:12,911
One of the principal figures, the most famous, was a monk, Buddhaghosa, who came from Buddhigaya, the place of Buddha's enlightenment.

71
00:07:13,651 --> 00:07:17,677
To prove his competence, he set about writing a summary of all the Buddha's teachings.

72
00:07:18,399 --> 00:07:25,351
The work is known as the Visuddhimagga, the Path of Freedom, and it is recognized as one of the greatest books on spiritual development ever produced.

73
00:07:27,156 --> 00:07:29,218
A lot of what I say here is taken from that book.

74
00:07:30,060 --> 00:07:36,773
Unfortunately, I don't recommend it to the beginner because it is a scholarly work, full of technical language and very dry, very dry indeed.

75
00:07:38,541 --> 00:07:43,350
Words are defined in this book in a way which seems strange to us, but actually illuminates a lot for us.

76
00:07:43,971 --> 00:07:44,994
That may be obscure.

77
00:07:45,735 --> 00:07:46,456
It's done like this.

78
00:07:46,916 --> 00:07:48,600
Take a flame, a flame of a match.

79
00:07:49,401 --> 00:07:52,307
The characteristic mark of a flame is heat.

80
00:07:52,908 --> 00:07:55,351
The function is to consume the wood.

81
00:07:56,194 --> 00:08:02,946
Its manifestation is light, and its near cause is the material to be burnt.

82
00:08:02,925 --> 00:08:09,713
It also has an inner enemy, damp in the material, and an outer enemy, an unexpected gust of wind.

83
00:08:10,934 --> 00:08:21,105
So a word is defined by its characteristic mark, its function, its manifestation, its near cause, its inner enemy and its outer enemy.

84
00:08:23,146 --> 00:08:28,392
Sympathetic joy, mudita, has as its characteristic mark the gladdening of others.

85
00:08:29,166 --> 00:08:31,250
When one is joyful, that joy is infective.

86
00:08:32,051 --> 00:08:36,937
How different it is when you work with someone who's happy, happy at their work and even happy by nature.

87
00:08:37,738 --> 00:08:44,407
Even when such a person is with someone who is depressed or angry, that inner joy undermines the despair, the hatred of the other.

88
00:08:45,788 --> 00:08:53,357
Its function is to do away with envy and jealousy so that it manifests itself as joy and happiness in others' success.

89
00:08:54,740 --> 00:08:58,784
Its near cause is the ability to rejoice in the success of others.

90
00:09:00,351 --> 00:09:06,077
How do we react when an acquaintance buys a better car than we have, when others get the promotion we wanted?

91
00:09:07,100 --> 00:09:15,408
You can see that this sort of joy, like equanimity, rests on non-attachment, that understanding of self, me, of mine, as only conventional truths.

92
00:09:16,809 --> 00:09:28,923
If we can only be joyful for ourselves and expect others to be happy at our success, our capacity for joy is greatly diminished, for we shall be overcome by envy and jealousy of others.

93
00:09:29,258 --> 00:09:33,524
This is the inner enemy, only being able to rejoice in oneself.

94
00:09:34,404 --> 00:09:40,293
That's why mudita is termed sympathetic joy, because our sense of joy should be universal.

95
00:09:40,974 --> 00:09:48,644
When it is universal, it will lack its outer edges of aversion, envy, jealousy and boredom, and naturally rejoice in others.

96
00:09:50,868 --> 00:09:54,793
Cultivating this sympathetic joy is also important for meditators.

97
00:09:55,177 --> 00:10:02,291
No matter how we feel inside, depressed, anxious, frustrated and so on, our hearts are turned outwards to be with others in a joyful way.

98
00:10:03,153 --> 00:10:09,745
Some people think this is false, that it's two-faced, but it's only two-faced if we pretend to be joyful.

99
00:10:10,214 --> 00:10:20,374
What we need to do is determine to put our attention into being with the other, to be with the other in a sympathetic, supportive and friendly way as the occasion demands.

100
00:10:21,255 --> 00:10:26,907
As to our internal moods, we can put them to the side for the time being and look at them later in meditation.

101
00:10:27,982 --> 00:10:43,106
It comes as a great surprise to those who practice this that the energy being absorbed by our negativity is displaced, drawn out of there into our positive disposition by the very will, the very intention to be positive, in this case joyful.

102
00:10:44,605 --> 00:10:46,187
This is the power of positive thinking.

103
00:10:46,947 --> 00:10:51,193
What's more, this joy turns up as one of the factors of enlightenment, here called piti.

104
00:10:51,894 --> 00:10:53,216
This is the joy of interest.

105
00:10:54,138 --> 00:11:01,849
As you determine to meditate, to cut through the moods and really concentrate, as you become absorbed, then that watchful interest will arise.

106
00:11:03,331 --> 00:11:09,960
That interest comes with joy and both are factors that need to be there for the intuitive faculty to activate and intuit nibbana.

107
00:11:10,581 --> 00:11:14,105
So here, we also have a solution for our boredom and depression.

108
00:11:14,474 --> 00:11:22,044
We find something to do, wholesome of course, we put our minds to it, and lo and behold, just by making the effort, interest and joy arise.

109
00:11:24,568 --> 00:11:29,456
Friendliness, open-heartedness, goodwill, loving-kindness, love in this sense is metta.

110
00:11:30,317 --> 00:11:36,486
All these qualities are its characteristic mark, and its function is to promote and develop these very qualities.

111
00:11:37,388 --> 00:11:43,096
The near cause that makes such a mind arise is the ability to see the lovableness in all beings.

112
00:11:44,004 --> 00:11:46,370
Here we come up against the problem of non-attachment.

113
00:11:47,393 --> 00:11:49,818
If I'm not supposed to be attached to anything, how can I love it?

114
00:11:50,660 --> 00:11:58,259
But attachment is when the object of love is defined as mine, belonging to me, or therefore my satisfaction.

115
00:11:59,042 --> 00:12:02,149
This is why affection and lust are the inner enemies.

116
00:12:02,938 --> 00:12:04,802
Your child comes home with a black eye.

117
00:12:05,042 --> 00:12:05,842
All hell's let loose.

118
00:12:06,163 --> 00:12:07,085
You want to know who did it.

119
00:12:07,485 --> 00:12:08,386
Why wasn't it stopped?

120
00:12:08,668 --> 00:12:09,528
You feel it terribly.

121
00:12:10,129 --> 00:12:13,916
When Jack the lad, the neighbour's son, comes home with a black eye, it's what he deserves.

122
00:12:14,135 --> 00:12:14,716
That'll teach him.

123
00:12:15,999 --> 00:12:24,111
That love of someone or something that we define as belonging to a me is what attached love is, attached to a definition of a me.

124
00:12:24,972 --> 00:12:27,596
Because of this, we love only what pleases us.

125
00:12:28,251 --> 00:12:37,306
If Victoria sees herself as a yuppie and has to walk down the street with a man dressed like a tramp, she'll keep a distance to make sure that everyone knows that he's not really with her.

126
00:12:38,187 --> 00:12:41,874
Such a man can never be her man, her boyfriend, her husband.

127
00:12:42,634 --> 00:12:47,282
This is why snobbery and classism are so destructive to relationships.

128
00:12:47,302 --> 00:12:51,229
Other people are turned into objects that signify a person's status.

129
00:12:51,589 --> 00:12:55,895
Just like cars, owning a Jaguar or a Mini says something about the owner.

130
00:12:57,630 --> 00:13:02,576
If a man has a Clint Eastwood complex, he doesn't want to be seen with a woman who doesn't look like Miss World.

131
00:13:03,397 --> 00:13:07,422
If he is with a woman who looks like Miss World, he feels wonderful.

132
00:13:08,062 --> 00:13:11,645
But if he's with a Miss Universe, he feels threatened and humiliated.

133
00:13:12,447 --> 00:13:15,691
He loves women only in that they enhance his image of himself.

134
00:13:16,471 --> 00:13:19,274
This is why sexism is so destructive to relationship.

135
00:13:19,774 --> 00:13:22,938
It turns the other into an object, an object which is there to please.

136
00:13:24,480 --> 00:13:27,604
If all these objects fail to please, then we hate them.

137
00:13:29,845 --> 00:13:33,428
When two people fall in love in sweet infatuation, what's happening?

138
00:13:34,330 --> 00:13:35,471
It's ego meet ego.

139
00:13:36,851 --> 00:13:42,719
On the physical, emotional and mental level, for those few precious days, weeks or months, it seems that two are one.

140
00:13:43,519 --> 00:13:48,244
The other looks supremely beautiful, is totally loving and kind and so intelligent.

141
00:13:49,144 --> 00:13:51,168
Then the charm begins to wear off.

142
00:13:51,187 --> 00:13:53,490
Suddenly, ego doesn't mirror ego.

143
00:13:54,668 --> 00:13:58,413
Before they know it, these two lovebirds are bickering and biting each other.

144
00:13:59,235 --> 00:14:03,442
If they break up, they say in a sort of bewildered way, I don't know what attracted me.

145
00:14:04,804 --> 00:14:11,417
Of course, in a long-lasting relationship, these times are overcome, but through a higher love not based on sensual attraction.

146
00:14:12,298 --> 00:14:19,090
This higher love, metta, will manifest as acceptance, goodwill, commitment, friendliness, care, and so on.

147
00:14:19,711 --> 00:14:25,793
If a partnership ever gets into a position of ill will and hatred, then it is consorting with the outer enemy.

148
00:14:26,918 --> 00:14:30,851
Lust and affection, or ill will, destroy true friendship.

149
00:14:31,337 --> 00:14:38,788
Lust centers on the personal physical satisfaction, the body beautiful, to the detriment of communication through touch and tenderness.

150
00:14:39,669 --> 00:14:49,244
Affection centers on the ego desires, what pleases me, without taking the other into consideration, and so feels to the other like an imprisonment.

151
00:14:50,125 --> 00:14:55,033
Ill will blocks any attempt of the other to approach or to make reconciliation.

152
00:14:56,498 --> 00:15:09,818
If we look at it another way, usually our attachments are first and foremost to our closest family, then relatives and friends, then place of birth, our country, then to the ethnic group or so-called race, and finally to all human beings.

153
00:15:10,760 --> 00:15:16,850
So long as our attachments always take this order, everything up the scale undermines, contradicts what's below.

154
00:15:17,691 --> 00:15:24,361
If my friend asks me for something, I don't see his request as independent, but in relation to these attachments.

155
00:15:24,409 --> 00:15:26,851
I only do that sort of thing for close family.

156
00:15:28,293 --> 00:15:31,476
If someone of another ethnic group has success, I moan.

157
00:15:32,216 --> 00:15:33,378
I say our group should have it.

158
00:15:34,620 --> 00:15:42,947
These attitudes reverse themselves and our hearts open up when we define ourselves first and foremost as human beings, then belonging to the different subgroups.

159
00:15:43,707 --> 00:15:49,273
This is one way to approach unbranded, impartial, universal, boundless love.

160
00:15:49,293 --> 00:15:51,075
This is what the Buddha meant by metta.

161
00:15:53,366 --> 00:15:54,568
Finally, there is compassion.

162
00:15:55,048 --> 00:16:00,735
According to the Visuddhimagga, the path of freedom, compassion has the characteristic of wanting to alleviate suffering.

163
00:16:01,778 --> 00:16:08,306
Its function is to make us unable to bear another person's suffering so that we are motivated to do something about it.

164
00:16:09,427 --> 00:16:12,630
Its near cause is the seeing of the helplessness in the sufferer.

165
00:16:13,432 --> 00:16:18,918
And when we act compassionately, it manifests as the opposite of cruelty, a caring concern.

166
00:16:19,912 --> 00:16:21,936
Cruelty itself is seen as the outer enemy.

167
00:16:22,216 --> 00:16:25,523
If we are cruel of heart, we enjoy inflicting pain on another.

168
00:16:26,043 --> 00:16:26,945
The exact opposite.

169
00:16:27,966 --> 00:16:32,174
The inner enemy, and this is difficult for us in the West to accept at first, is grief.

170
00:16:34,119 --> 00:16:38,427
To illustrate all this, I'd like to take a story from the magnificent Winnie the Pooh, Pooh Bear herself.

171
00:16:38,667 --> 00:16:43,235
No doubt, in my mind, a very enlightened being, even if only a bear of little brain.

172
00:16:43,807 --> 00:16:46,110
The story I'd like to centre on is Eeyore's birthday.

173
00:16:46,971 --> 00:16:50,177
When Pooh happens upon Eeyore, he's a very sad donkey indeed.

174
00:16:50,937 --> 00:16:52,360
Everyone's forgotten his birthday.

175
00:16:53,182 --> 00:16:58,229
Pooh, once he's realised what is wrong, it takes him a little while, decides to tackle the problem at heart.

176
00:16:59,110 --> 00:17:04,558
Even though he too had forgotten Eeyore's birthday, at least he could still get him a present and put things aright.

177
00:17:05,361 --> 00:17:08,885
He rushes off home, only to find Piglet knocking on his door.

178
00:17:09,440 --> 00:17:13,925
When Piglet finds out it's Pooh's birthday, he wants to share Pooh's present.

179
00:17:13,945 --> 00:17:18,171
Pooh tells him that that's not a good idea, so Piglet rushes off to get a present of his own.

180
00:17:19,292 --> 00:17:21,295
Pooh decides to give Eeyore a jar of honey.

181
00:17:22,276 --> 00:17:26,020
Unfortunately on the way, none too mindful, he gets a little peckish and eats the honey.

182
00:17:26,862 --> 00:17:32,950
When he realises what he's done, he saves the day by realising he can give the empty jar to Eeyore as a useful pot.

183
00:17:33,857 --> 00:17:44,933
Little Piglet, meanwhile, went to get a balloon left over from a party and is racing towards Eeyore, hoping to get there before Pooh to give Eeyore the impression that he'd remembered his birthday without anyone telling him.

184
00:17:45,615 --> 00:17:47,758
Unfortunately, he slips and bursts the balloon.

185
00:17:48,979 --> 00:17:53,065
In the end, Piglet arrives with the burst balloon and Pooh with his useful pot.

186
00:17:53,128 --> 00:18:05,666
After a heart-rending scene, they leave Eeyore as happy as a donkey could be, for Eeyore, though disappointed with the balloon being burst, has now found a wonderful pastime, putting it in and pulling it out of his useful pot.

187
00:18:07,028 --> 00:18:09,833
To get the full delight of the story, please read the originals.

188
00:18:10,674 --> 00:18:12,758
The conversation is very funny.

189
00:18:13,979 --> 00:18:21,329
Anyway, the point of my retelling the story here is to point out what compassion is, and how Pooh Bear here is without doubt a very compassionate little being.

190
00:18:22,019 --> 00:18:26,510
When Pooh sees Eeyore and hears his tale, he doesn't do what we would likely do.

191
00:18:26,892 --> 00:18:29,597
He doesn't collude and build up a world of woe.

192
00:18:29,999 --> 00:18:31,943
Yes, you're right, Eeyore, the world's terrible.

193
00:18:32,105 --> 00:18:33,488
Nobody remembers birthdays.

194
00:18:33,808 --> 00:18:34,932
People aren't kind anymore.

195
00:18:34,971 --> 00:18:35,493
It's rotten.

196
00:18:35,693 --> 00:18:38,019
The world, the people in it, and so on and so on.

197
00:18:38,724 --> 00:18:44,012
We think that this indulgence of self-pity and righteous indignation is a way of consoling someone.

198
00:18:44,433 --> 00:18:50,123
But in fact, this sort of self-indulgent whinging simply adds to the overall feelings of depression and sorrow.

199
00:18:50,824 --> 00:18:56,593
It's bad enough for Eeyore to realise that everyone's forgotten his birthday without being told that that's how the world really is.

200
00:18:58,075 --> 00:19:04,125
The other course we would take is the, oh come on, pull your socks off Eeyore, and the kick in the pants routine.

201
00:19:05,167 --> 00:19:09,011
No pity here, but anger and aversion, as in others' depression and self-pity.

202
00:19:10,012 --> 00:19:17,099
Of course, such an action would be to oppress poor Eeyore the more, seeing that no one understands his sorrow and actually blames him for it.

203
00:19:17,880 --> 00:19:19,842
No, Pooh Bear does neither.

204
00:19:21,042 --> 00:19:22,625
They had all forgotten Eeyore's birthday.

205
00:19:22,785 --> 00:19:23,566
That's the problem.

206
00:19:24,026 --> 00:19:24,567
What to do?

207
00:19:25,488 --> 00:19:29,151
Off he goes to get a present, thereby turning the situation into one of joy.

208
00:19:29,892 --> 00:19:33,875
That's compassion, treating the problem, allaying the suffering.

209
00:19:34,919 --> 00:19:41,227
Piglet, of course, wants to do that also, but he also wants to give Eeyore the wrong impression that he's remembered his birthday.

210
00:19:41,826 --> 00:19:43,869
He wants to be Eeyore's best friend.

211
00:19:44,529 --> 00:19:48,115
It's still compassion, all right, but compassion with ego added.

212
00:19:50,376 --> 00:19:52,519
We can test our compassion in ordinary daily life.

213
00:19:53,020 --> 00:19:55,242
What is our reaction to other people's suffering?

214
00:19:55,262 --> 00:19:55,983
Do we ignore it?

215
00:19:56,084 --> 00:19:57,405
Do we get irritated by it?

216
00:19:57,806 --> 00:20:00,910
Do we want to do something about it purely or for recognition?

217
00:20:01,665 --> 00:20:08,532
Unfortunately, until our hearts are totally purified, all our compassionate actions will have some small ingredient of ego in there somewhere.

218
00:20:09,773 --> 00:20:20,085
Whenever we help someone, we need to be aware, just aware of such reactions, the wholesome one of compassion, and the unwholesome ones of indifference, aversion, selfishness, pride, and so on.

219
00:20:20,105 --> 00:20:28,534
Just notice the unwholesome ones, don't entertain them, don't pay any attention to them, don't give them any importance, don't entertain any feelings of guilt.

220
00:20:29,509 --> 00:20:34,083
Realize that all such thoughts and feelings are just products of past unwholesome conditioning.

221
00:20:35,247 --> 00:20:38,435
Put all the energy we have into solving the problem.

222
00:20:39,057 --> 00:20:41,223
Solving the problem is what compassion is.

223
00:20:41,878 --> 00:20:49,650
While solving the problem, we may need to console, to empathize, to say encouraging things, but the real motivation is to solve the problem.

224
00:20:50,592 --> 00:21:00,547
If after our action we feel good, we notice how much we esteem ourselves, how good we think we are, that's just the product of the ego-added ingredient to our good actions.

225
00:21:00,807 --> 00:21:01,288
Let it be.

226
00:21:02,368 --> 00:21:08,719
For if we entertain such thoughts, we shall find ourselves doing good in order to feel good ourselves.

227
00:21:09,460 --> 00:21:11,041
That's the do-gooder complex.

228
00:21:11,443 --> 00:21:20,443
If you've ever been the object of the attentions of a do-gooder, you'll understand what I mean when I say that the sufferer becomes a patient, an object to be taken care of.

229
00:21:21,445 --> 00:21:22,669
It can be quite stifling.

230
00:21:23,329 --> 00:21:28,582
It is impossible to be totally compassionate so long as there is ego, selfishness within us.

231
00:21:29,463 --> 00:21:31,208
But we still have to strive.

232
00:21:31,508 --> 00:21:36,952
In the striving, we will discover selfish attitudes underlying our compassion, the inner enemies.

233
00:21:37,614 --> 00:21:43,398
Slowly, this wisdom will lead to separating out those selfish elements until they become isolated.

234
00:21:44,160 --> 00:21:50,125
In their isolation, they will lose their influence over us and seem like cheeky flies to be gently wafted away.

235
00:21:53,088 --> 00:21:55,770
Doing what we can to alleviate another's suffering is enough.

236
00:21:56,551 --> 00:21:57,893
We can only do what we can do.

237
00:21:58,292 --> 00:21:59,894
What's the point of grief?

238
00:22:00,009 --> 00:22:01,892
Pooh does not grieve over Eeyore's plight.

239
00:22:02,333 --> 00:22:03,594
Pooh doesn't start to cry over it.

240
00:22:04,315 --> 00:22:16,029
If I go to the doctor to find out the results of an X-ray, and he pulls it out, holds it to the light, points tremblingly at the dark spot, and collapses into a heap of sobs while telling me I only have three weeks to live, how does that make me feel?

241
00:22:16,851 --> 00:22:26,423
Here am I, trying to come to terms with this traumatic news, while a part of me wants to comfort the doctor, is embarrassed by the doctor, is angry that the doctor isn't consoling me, giving me some hope.

242
00:22:27,601 --> 00:22:30,584
Now, I'm not saying here that we have to repress our grief, not at all.

243
00:22:30,884 --> 00:22:33,006
If we feel grief and sorrow, we have to let it out.

244
00:22:33,326 --> 00:22:34,666
It's most necessary to do so.

245
00:22:35,208 --> 00:22:38,410
But we also have to recognize that it is not a wholesome state of mind.

246
00:22:39,651 --> 00:22:48,239
If we think we have to grieve, then we may very well be reinforcing the grief and find ourselves grieving all our lives over a mistake or a loss of someone dear.

247
00:22:48,838 --> 00:22:49,740
It can become an illness.

248
00:22:50,760 --> 00:22:56,645
The fact is that the amount of grief we feel is proportionate to our attachment to that thing or person.

249
00:22:57,182 --> 00:22:59,085
If my mother is suffering, I feel terrible.

250
00:22:59,385 --> 00:23:01,268
If it's your mother, I feel sad for you.

251
00:23:01,807 --> 00:23:03,390
If it's Mrs. Bloggs, I don't feel anything.

252
00:23:03,450 --> 00:23:04,411
I don't know Mrs. Bloggs.

253
00:23:05,813 --> 00:23:10,097
If a doctor weeps over the suffering of her husband, we think that's right and proper.

254
00:23:10,538 --> 00:23:13,461
But if she does it over a patient, we think that's unprofessional.

255
00:23:16,045 --> 00:23:21,111
Furthermore, if I myself am grieving, if I'm upset, that hinders my ability to be compassionate.

256
00:23:21,671 --> 00:23:23,173
I was once in an accident.

257
00:23:23,592 --> 00:23:24,553
I ran over a dog.

258
00:23:24,973 --> 00:23:32,303
When I went into the pub opposite to ask whose it was, the landlady rushed out, shrieked, picked up the dog, and stood there wailing and shouting.

259
00:23:32,824 --> 00:23:35,426
The dog was in its death throes, with blood pouring out of its mouth.

260
00:23:35,587 --> 00:23:42,916
She was absolutely grief-stricken, so stricken she could do nothing at all for the dog, and probably added to the dog's suffering by handling it.

261
00:23:44,280 --> 00:23:46,626
It's difficult for us to grasp this point about grief.

262
00:23:46,807 --> 00:23:47,910
We need to ponder over it.

263
00:23:48,612 --> 00:24:02,424
Once we realise that grief doesn't help, once we realise that a lot of our grief can be caused by the fact that we think we ought to grieve and feel guilty if we don't, we can let go of a lot of our grief, not give it importance, just let it die out.

264
00:24:03,990 --> 00:24:06,375
There's a famous story from the scriptures illustrating this point.

265
00:24:06,756 --> 00:24:09,039
Kisargottami brought her dead child to the Buddha.

266
00:24:09,319 --> 00:24:11,804
She was absolutely distraught with grief.

267
00:24:11,824 --> 00:24:16,673
She had heard of his powers and wanted him to perform some ceremony or other to bring the child back to life.

268
00:24:17,473 --> 00:24:19,577
The Buddha realized that talking would not help.

269
00:24:20,179 --> 00:24:24,066
He asked her instead to leave the child with him and go in search of a mustard seed.

270
00:24:24,787 --> 00:24:27,230
Now mustard seeds are a thousand a penny in India.

271
00:24:27,650 --> 00:24:32,095
Kisagatami ran off full of joy thinking that the Buddha would now bring her child back to life.

272
00:24:32,655 --> 00:24:34,458
But the Buddha had put a condition on it.

273
00:24:34,978 --> 00:24:38,782
He had said the seed must come from a house where there had been no death.

274
00:24:39,683 --> 00:24:44,568
Every house she visited they were only too glad to give her handfuls of mustard seeds.

275
00:24:45,089 --> 00:24:47,692
But to the last they all had a death to report.

276
00:24:48,032 --> 00:24:50,316
A grandfather, a grandmother, a parent, a child.

277
00:24:51,105 --> 00:24:55,671
Slowly, slowly, it dawned on Gisagotami that death was inevitable and inescapable.

278
00:24:56,471 --> 00:24:59,253
As her insight came, the madness of her grief passed.

279
00:24:59,875 --> 00:25:02,597
She returned, praising the Buddha, and later joined the Order.

280
00:25:03,137 --> 00:25:05,079
Eventually, she achieved full enlightenment.

281
00:25:06,101 --> 00:25:12,487
Anyone who has done bereavement counselling knows that the hardest thing for the grieved to accept is that the beloved one has died.

282
00:25:13,208 --> 00:25:17,011
It's so difficult to say, John's dead, Mary's dead.

283
00:25:17,768 --> 00:25:23,679
The Great Compassionate One, the Buddha, the helper of humankind, is asking us to see things as they really are.

284
00:25:24,500 --> 00:25:29,950
It's painful to let go of our cherished notions, but when we do, we experience liberation.

285
00:25:30,771 --> 00:25:35,740
Like Kisagotami, we need to liberate ourselves from wrong views, wrong understandings.

286
00:25:36,623 --> 00:25:39,607
I'm sure she went on to help many another in grief.

287
00:25:42,102 --> 00:25:46,326
I hope that all this has gone a long way to scotch the idea that Buddhism is a cold religion.

288
00:25:47,127 --> 00:25:51,633
That Buddha was teaching some cold indifference that non-attachment means not to care.

289
00:25:52,773 --> 00:25:58,740
In the Metta Sutta, the Discourse on Loving Kindness, the Buddha urges people to live always in the mind of universal love.

290
00:25:59,622 --> 00:26:02,806
He asks us to cultivate a love like a mother who is not possessive.

291
00:26:03,967 --> 00:26:05,890
Children are in the care of parents.

292
00:26:06,029 --> 00:26:06,990
They don't belong to them.

293
00:26:08,132 --> 00:26:09,534
People are in our care.

294
00:26:09,713 --> 00:26:11,316
They don't belong to us.

295
00:26:11,751 --> 00:26:19,182
If we can cultivate this attitude, then we will be like the mother, who is equanimous with the leaving of the eldest.

296
00:26:19,201 --> 00:26:20,944
She has gone on and is doing well.

297
00:26:21,265 --> 00:26:22,747
There's no sorrow in the parting.

298
00:26:22,968 --> 00:26:23,669
The job's done.

299
00:26:24,990 --> 00:26:27,094
The child, now adult, must go her own way.

300
00:26:28,556 --> 00:26:33,102
The second child has just passed his exams and she feels sympathetic joy at his success.

301
00:26:33,461 --> 00:26:35,244
She encourages him to succeed the more.

302
00:26:36,346 --> 00:26:37,688
The third is at school and young.

303
00:26:38,229 --> 00:26:41,673
She takes care to support the child, guiding her as a true friend.

304
00:26:42,615 --> 00:26:59,156
the youngest is in bed with a bad sore throat and cold to that child she feels nothing but compassion devoting herself to alleviating his suffering this mother lives in the divine abodes her heart is forever in loving-kindness compassion sympathetic joy or equanimity

305
00:27:01,397 --> 00:27:03,742
The Buddha tells us to develop these states of mind.

306
00:27:04,644 --> 00:27:09,073
It is the measure of our personal growth in the meditative life the more we live in these states.

307
00:27:10,035 --> 00:27:21,297
He asks us to practice sending out our loving-kindness, compassion, sympathetic joy and peace in all directions, east, south, west, north, below and above, to cover the whole universe with these thoughts.

308
00:27:21,798 --> 00:27:23,540
These were his instructions.

309
00:27:24,803 --> 00:27:35,362
Here a disciple dwells, pervading in one direction with heart filled with love, likewise in the second, the third, the fourth direction, so above, below, and around.

310
00:27:36,143 --> 00:27:47,502
He dwells pervading the entire world everywhere, and equally with heart filled with love, abundant, grown great, measureless, free from hatred, and free from distress.

311
00:27:49,119 --> 00:27:54,545
And this is done again with compassion, and then with sympathetic joy, and lastly with equanimity.

312
00:27:56,686 --> 00:27:59,970
This is how we should end any vipassana insight meditation we do.

313
00:28:00,750 --> 00:28:07,798
What mental energy we have purified is thereby transformed, re-educated, re-conditioned into one of those sublime states.

314
00:28:08,838 --> 00:28:10,079
Our training continues.

315
00:28:10,641 --> 00:28:18,367
These states deepen and broaden until, like all the Buddhas and Arahats, we shall live continually in these four divine abodes.

316
00:28:19,174 --> 00:28:21,098
worth striving for, don't you think?

317
00:28:23,644 --> 00:28:26,810
So I hope this talk has been interesting and helpful.

318
00:28:27,893 --> 00:28:29,717
May all of you be happy and peaceful.

319
00:28:30,538 --> 00:28:33,505
May all of you attain the nirvanic peace within.

